,"en":{"1230–1303":"1230–1303","1240–1273":"1240–1273","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1200–1290":"1200–1290","1210–1231":"1210–1231","1231":"1231","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","ABT 1260":"about 1260","1304":"1304","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1231":"about 1231","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Castle Cary,,,England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Castle Cary, Somersetshire, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Donegal and Westmeath) and English: variant of   Carey  .","French: variant of   Carry   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Decorah","meanings":["Americanized form of <b>de Carrie</b>, itself an altered form of French <b>Decary</b>, a variant of   Cary   2, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’. It is found mainly among the Ho-Chunk (i.e. Winnebago) Native American people in WI.","History: The progenitor of the Decorahs was a French soldier, Joseph Sabrevoir de Carrie, who in 1729 settled for a time among the Winnebagos on Doty Island, WI, and married an Indian woman, known in English as Glory of the Morning. Decorah, a city in IA, is named after one of their descendants, Waukon Decorah (<i>c.</i> 1780–1868), a chief of the Winnebago."]},{"name":"Carey","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardha</b>, a midland surname meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ciardha</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>ciar</i> ‘dark, black’. See   Kerry  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhiachra</b> ‘son of <i>Fiachra</i>’.","English: from Carey Barton in Devon or Castle Cary, Lytes Cary, Cary Fitzpaine, or Babcary, all in Somerset, named for the rivers on which they stand; both river names probably derive from the Celtic root <i>car-</i> ‘love, liking’, perhaps with the meaning ‘pleasant stream’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Cary was born in 1230, in Devon, England, his father, John de Kary, was 30 and his mother, Elizabeth Stapleton, was 21. He married Alicet Beaumont in 1270, in Castle Cary, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. His occupation is listed as lord of the manors of west polworth, paveston and karry in Devon, England, United Kingdom. He died in 1303, in his hometown, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1230–1303":"1230–1303","1240–1273":"1240–1273","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1200–1290":"1200–1290","1210–1231":"1210–1231","1231":"1231","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","ABT 1260":"umbes 1260","1304":"1304","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1231":"umb